Sub-Saharan African Stocks Report: KenolKobil, Oando Are Active

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-08-17T16:02:08Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-17/sub-saharan-african-stocks-report-kenolkobil-oando-are-active.html
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index fell for
the first day in four, shedding 0.3 percent to 1,949.34 by the
1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .  Kenya’s All-Share Index snapped two days of gains.
retreating 0.1 percent to 62.13 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi,
the capital. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index gained
for a second day, rising 0.1 percent to 22,811.39 by the 2:30
p.m. close in Lagos, according to a statement on the bourse’s
website.  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  advanced 1.1
percent to 783.92 by 4 p.m. in Windhoek. The Ghana Stock
Exchange Composite Index gained for a second day, adding less
than 0.1 percent to 1,178.90 by 3 p.m. in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  KenolKobil Ltd. (KNOC KN), a Kenyan fuel retailer with
operations in nine African countries, rallied to the highest in
more than a week, rising 15 cents, or 1.4 percent, to 11.25
shillings. Oil advanced from a two-day low in  New York  as
investors bet that shrinking fuel stockpiles in the U.S.
indicate demand will increase in the world’s biggest crude-
consuming nation.  Oando Plc (OANDO)  , a Nigerian petroleum products
company, gained for a second day, advancing 50 kobo, or 1.8
percent, to 29 naira.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Stephen Gunnion in Johannesburg at 
 sgunnion@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
